commentBody:
@Cat Lady Margaret If the clue was

What fits the Venn diagram of *both* "Computers" and "Pastas"?

Would you find that satisfactory? I agree that that would be better clueing, but I think the words fits and ands make the clueing acceptable even without the word both

@Cat Lady Margaret So, where the circles overlap you find those elements that are common to both sets. That's the sense the clue refers to, synonymous with intersection, which I would say is how most people understand it.

That's as far as I go. I tried to understand the additional distinctions you make, and I even took a look at Wikipedia, but it's too confusing for me! 

I'm ok with Edith Pritchett's Venn diagram cartoons in the Guardian, for what it's worth, but I usually go straight to First Dog on the Moon.

@Elly Zee 
We all shed skin cells all the time; much of the 'dust' we dustmop/sweep/swab from the floor is composed of the (dead, colorless) skin cells.  These show up more on your skin if your normal skin tone is darker, but the take-away is:  we all need to moisturize more.  
When I pull off a pair of knee socks and see the shower of skin cells, I'm kind of horrified; I think it gets worse with age.

@suejean 

Jet lag is pernicious and subtle and lasts much longer than most people allow for.

Glad you keep coming back.

@LJADZ 

This comes up every time she's clued that way in a puzzle.  And since both of her names contain a lot of useful letters, she appears a lot.  

It's something that, regrettably, we have to live with, because they'll always use her name in puzzles, and it doesn't seem likely they're going to change the clue to "She broke up the Beatles".

@Hardroch 

The quibble is that the item is called a fish hook or fishhook.  While that is the dominant term, today's answer is not unheard of:

