@David Connell 

That sounds much like the recipe we used to use. It’s been a long time since we’ve made salsa verde. 

I was surprised (though I shouldn’t have been) by the number of comments about not having heard of TOMATILLOs before.

@Mean Old Lady 
Childish Gambino, when not doing music, is Donald Glover, maybe best known at this point for creating and starring on the tv series Atlanta, which I think was on FX. 
He had a small, but crucial, role in the movie The Martian, which I recently watched again and enjoyed on cable.

@Damon from Austin 

Hard to describe the thrill as each successive letter turns up green.

I got it in one once.  How I wished I'd been paying more attention as it happened.  I almost missed it altogether, taking a sip of coffee.

@Floridaworder That a great way to look at at it. But this is the land of needless replies, extreme fact-checking and dictionary weaponizing. 

It is what it 
is. Gotta love it.

@Ettagale 

First of all, it's actually still a spoiler, since it's now possible to do previous Bees (up to a week, I think).  Many people may have left it open to continue at their leisure.

But as long as the cat is out of the bag, I'll mention that the word in question is not only a place but a type of liqueur that originated there.  If you go there, they'll be glad to take you on a tour of their facilities.

@Ettagale 
I visited that particular island many years ago, the first Caribbean island I ever went to. There wasn’t much to do or see there, but the colorful houses in Willemstad reminiscent of canal houses in Amsterdam were very impressive. As Steve L pointed out,  a visit to Landhuis Chobolobo where they make the liqueur is actually pretty fun. For a sense of the place check out:

www.chobolobo.com

